{{Infobox person | name = Edward Boches | image = Edward Boches.JPG | caption = Edward Boches in 2010 | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|3|21}} | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | residence = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] | nationality = [[United States]] | website = {{URL|http://edwardboches.com}} | occupation = professor, creative director, brand consultant }}
'''Edward Boches''' is an [[United States|American]] professor at [[Boston University]]’s [[Boston_University_College_of_Communication|College of Communication]] where he has taught advertising and creative courses since 2012.<ref>[http://www.bu.edu/com/about-com/faculty/edward-boches/ Boston University College of Communication Faculty]</ref> Previously he was a partner, chief innovation officer,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/22/business/media/22addes.html New York Times, News from the Advertising Industry]</ref> chief creative officer and executive creative director at the ad agency Mullen, where he worked for 31 years.<ref>[http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/mullen-ups-boches-executive-cd-21884 AdWeek ''Mullen Ups Boches to ECD'']</ref><ref>[http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/new-roles-wenneker-boches-mullen-103840 AdWeek ''New Roles for Wenneker, Boches'']</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ooXXuFMQrBcC&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=edward+boches+named+chief+innovation+officer+mullen&source=bl&ots=nBpWw5YJZ_&sig=a0pM0AVkTFl5z6vD-CgZvtUFNC4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HGmlVN6vIIHZggSB3YLIDQ&ved=0CFIQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=edward%20boches%20named%20chief%20innovation%20officer%20mullen&f=false ''Advertisers at Work'' by Tracy Tuten]</ref>
==Career== Boches joined Mullen in 1983 as a vice president/account director and director of public relations. He launched the agency's PR practice and shortly afterward joined the creative department. During his tenure at the agency he created campaigns for brands that included General Motors, Panera Bread, Lending Tree, Smartfood Popcorn, LL Bean, and Monster.com, including the job board's ''When I Grow Up'' Super Bowl commercial.<ref>[http://adage.com/article/news/monster-show/58137/ Ad Age: ''Monster.com Best of Show]''</ref> His campaigns were recognized by international, national and regional creative awards including Cannes, the One Show, New York Art Directors, the Clio Awards and Hatch, where he won Best of Show in 1990.<ref>[http://business.highbeam.com/2935/article-1P2-8194513/rising-stars-boston-ad-wars Boston Globe: ''Rising Stars in Boston Ad Wars'']</ref> In 1990 he was named print copywriter of the year by AdWeek.
He was an early industry advocate for the use of Twitter and social media.<ref>[http://www.commarts.com/columns/world-has-changed Communication Arts: ''The World has Changed'']</ref> encouraging the use of new platforms long before they were popular.<ref>[http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/what-can-twitter-do-you-98866 AdWeek: ''What Twitter Can Do for You'']</ref> In 2011, he created "Brand Bowl",<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9kn87w8-zRsC&pg=PT114&dq=edward+boches&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xAamVMHRDMLXgwSMjITADg&ved=0CDQQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=edward%20boches&f=false David Meerman Scott: ''The New Rules of Marketing and PR'']</ref> which used Twitter to monitor and measure reaction to Super Bowl advertising.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/07/business/media/for-super-bowl-ads-no-standout-performer.html?_r=0 New York Times ''For Super Bowl Ads, No Standout Performer'']</ref>
While chief innovation officer, ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'' named Mullen the fourth most innovative marketing company in the US in 2011.<ref>[http://www.fastcompany.com/3017618/most-innovative-companies-2011/most-innovative-companies-2011-top-10-in-advertising Fast Company: ''Most Innovative Marketing Companies'']</ref>
Boches left the agency in 2014, having worked his last two years part-time in order to transition into his career as a professor.
