'''Einar Enger''' (born 16 August 1950) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] business executive who is chief executive officer of [[Norwegian State Railways]].

He was educated as an agrarian economist from the [[Norwegian University of Life Sciences|Norwegian College of Agriculture]] and worked for the [[agricultural cooperatives in Norway]]. He was the chief executive officer of [[Tine (company)|Tine]] and [[Fellesmeieriet]], as well as regional director and marketing director in [[Gilde Norsk Kjøtt]]. He was appointed chief executive officer of the Norwegian State Railways in 2001.<ref name=nsb>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124221708/http://www.nsb.no/internet/no/Om_NSB/NSB_Konsern_Organisasjon/index.jhtml |archivedate=24 January 2007 |url=http://www.nsb.no/internet/no/Om_NSB/NSB_Konsern_Organisasjon/index.jhtml?language=no |title=Konsernledelse |author=Norges Statsbaner |language=Norwegian |accessdate=2007-07-21 |authorlink=Norwegian State Railways |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> He assumed office in March 2001, and took over after acting president [[Arne Wam]], after several months of turbulence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Enger: – Jeg har noe NSB vil satse på|date=12 December 2000|agency=Norwegian News Agency}}</ref> In November 2010 he announced his intent to resign in early 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/article3908914.ece |title=Har ikke tro på lyntog i Norge |last=Bentzrød |first=Sveinung Berg |author2=Nygaard, Knut |date=17 November 2010 |work=Aftenposten |language=Norwegian |accessdate=14 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629162214/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/article3908914.ece |archivedate=29 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> He left in May 2011, and was succeeded by acting executive [[Arne Fosen]] as the State Railways had not yet hired a successor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/okonomi/innland/article4121040.ece |title=Gigalønn frister få |last=Holm |first=Per Annar |date=14 May 2011 |work=Aftenposten |language=Norwegian |accessdate=14 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513202603/http://www.aftenposten.no/okonomi/innland/article4121040.ece |archivedate=13 May 2011 |df= }}</ref>

